I find it maddening that a woman can ACCUSE a man and play the victim to ruin his life, AND can be arrested for assaulting another woman in 2009 and somehow still be some champion of abused women. You can't have it both ways. 

I wish MORE people looked at the court documents where you threatened to accuse Johnny Depp of Domestic Violence if he didn't give in to your gold digging demands! You hoped he would roll over on the fear of losing his career, but he didn't and now he's viewed as a villain.

YOU refused to do your deposition because you had about 4 witnesses to Depp's over 70 and you knew you'd lose.

You didn't donate the 7 Million to charity out of the goodness of your heart, you did it as part of the Non-disclosure agreement that you and Depp signed stating he wouldn't tell the world the truth about you.

comment:
"Aquaman" was a billion dollar success... but only because it heavily appealed to the Eastern audience.  In the United States, it made $335,061,807.  The audience in the Orient doesn't care who plays Mera.  They are there for the special effects (now that the US has such a contentious relationship with China, we will see how well American movies do overseas.)  I agree that Jason Momoa was the star, and the success rests on his shoulders...but a team of reviewers pointed out how he tries not to look at Mera during their romantic scenes, and once you see it, you can't unsee it.  The two had zero chemistry between them (have you *seen* Game of Thrones?) In their romantic scenes, Ms. Heard *IS* on camera with her own, true love.... but she loves herself and no one else, and it shows.  As for her star power, the two movies that Amber Heard made directly before "Aquaman" were "Her Smell" $260,481,  and "London Fields" $487,420 (in which Ms. Heard was the star, and which has the dubious distinction of having the second worse release in the history of film) which *combined* didn't have a worldwide gross of one million dollars.  

As to the ongoing litigation... women are constantly crying that they are not treated the same way men are.  *Amber Heard was arrested for the domestic assault of her wife, Tasya van Ree, at the request of her wife, Tasya van Ree, in 2009, in the Seattle/Tacoma International Airport.*  The assault was witnessed by an airport full of people and both of the arresting officers.  The WB has asked Mr. Depp to leave his role in the "Fantastic Beasts" series... *so why does Amber Heard still have any jobs?*  If she were a man, she never would have been hired, with a domestic abuse arrest on her record.  I suspect Warner Brothers have backed the wrong horse on this one, and when the case is finished litigation, Mr. Depp will be exonerated, and Ms. Heard will be on her way to jail.  No one is going to forget that they allowed Amber Heard to keep working, but they asked for Johnny Depp's resignation.  *EQUALITY* right, Amber... that *IS* what you are fighting for?  ...and the right to keep all the money that you promised would go to charity... 

Depp and Heard didn't have *ANY* Court Case, until the Virginia Trial.  The British Trial was between Mr. Depp and *Dan Wootton* (who works with Judge Nicol's son, Robert Palmer, at TalkRADIO, the sister company to "The Sun"), and *NGN,* parent company of "The Sun" and owned by Rupert Murdoch (who is the employer of Judge Nicole's son, Robert Palmer)  Ms. Heard was just a witness at that trial.  As Ms. Heard only wrote the article which caused the Virginia lawsuit in December 2018, the truth is that Mr. Depp did not bring suit against her until 2019, *NOT 2017.* 

Emilia Clarke is an outstanding actor, and she has great chemistry with Jason Momoa.  She would be a great replacement, and Warner Brothers would add the "GOT" fans to the "Aquaman" fans... so it would be win/win!
